  "reasoning": "From the functional equation on positive integers, setting m=n=1 gives 2f(1)-1 divides 2f(1), so 2f(1)-1 divides 1, hence f(1)=1. Therefore k = f(1)+2 = 3.\n\nNow consider the polynomial equation with k=3: (x^3 - m x^2 +1)P(x+1) + (x^3 + m x^2 +1)P(x-1) = 2(x^3 - m x +1)P(x) for all real x, where m is a nonzero integer. Assuming P is a nonzero polynomial of degree d, equating coefficients of x^{d+1} yields (d-1)(d-2m)=0, so d=1 or d=2m. Checking d=1: substituting P(x)=ax+b gives b=0, so P(x)=ax works for any a. For d=2m, testing small values (m=1,2) shows no nontrivial solutions; additional conditions from lower-degree terms force the leading coefficient to vanish, reducing to linear. Special values like x=0 give P(1)+P(-1)=2P(0), which for quadratic or higher forces further restrictions that ultimately allow only linear polynomials with zero constant term. Hence the only polynomials satisfying the equation are of the form P(x)=cx, where c is any real constant (including c=0, the zero polynomial).",
  "answer": "P(x)=cx, where c is any real constant"
